Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: I found Frog Run and established an acceptable site to collect data.   I hope to use a site about 50 feet from Bridge 2.72 which crosses the stream just before an adjacent stream Little Sandy Creek joins with Frog Run. There appears to be a drainage pipe from a field on the right of the stream looking upstream and a spring directly across from the pipe on the left of the stream.  Our site is located above these two sites. I talked with both the neighbors and the landowner and obtained permission to conduct the data.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments:
The stream was very high and fast moving.  The area was saturated due to heavy snow melt and rain.  Water was pooled in nearby fields.  We thought it would still be a beneficial data collection since it reflected early spring thaw with accompanying participation and high water.
The road that leads to the site was in good condition with few pot holes and grass growing in and along the ditches.  Water was contained in the ditches and was not running on the road.  The stream was at the top on the banks but not overflowing.  It was cloudy and not muddy.  We were able to see our boots and the rocks on the bottom even though the water was fast and high.  We did not collect data from the center of the stream due to the high water but chose to collect samples just off the bank at our chosen site.  We chose to estimate the height of the stream by stepping off the bank and putting the stick in about 4 feet from the bank.  We also estimated the width of the stream from the bridge by eyeing the site and pulling the tape to find an approximate width.  We used a large stick to determine the rate the water moved by dropping it in at our site and timing it to the bridge.  We did this test twice.
We talked with the neighbors and were told that trout have been caught by the neighbor from this stream.  The landowner stopped by to ask about our findings and he shared that it was a 'good stream.'
We noted that there is a sizable spring draining into Frog Run just below our site and that Little Sandy creek appears to be a smaller stream at this point.  Both may be good to monitor in the future.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: We ran into a couple of guys at this site parked in their trucks talking just down from the boring site where work was ongoing even on Sunday. One was a pipeline supervisor from Houston. The other was an 'environmental specialist' working for Applied who was from Tennessee. They talked to us for a good half hour and told us how diligent and careful the company had been. I noted the lack of WVians employed and the Applied man said that most WVians just wanted to sit around and collect government money. He said the farmers deer and cows loved the grass they planted and wasn't it nice of them to improve the land by clearing it and planting grass. When I observed that the water was orange he wanted to blame it on AMD even though this color was not observed before pipeline work began.

Additional Comments: Well cobbled creek, moderate flow at October sampling. During a scouting trip 9-15-16 the bed was a small trickle with pooling under the bridge. Minnows but not as numerous as both upstream and downstream monitoring points. Pebble count and sampling area 66ft downstream of center of bridge (from stage measuring point). NW side of stream is bounded by cattle field, but fenced in - cattle do not have access to stream. Stream is private land, and shows little traffic, foot or vehicular, on either bank. Bank very brushy. Downstream of pebble count transects, about another 30m, there is steep dirt hillside on SE side that shows severe erosion. Stream bed takes on more silt at that point, downstream of that the creek returns to a more cobbled bed with riparian banks, but all this is outside my sampling area.
Additional Comments_1: Found new landowner, apparently the Ralstons, who gave me written permission, do not own all of the monitoring area - Mr Gary Cooper visited me while I was monitoring and I learned that he owned the land I accessed the stream from, and the streambed. He was nonetheless enthusiastic about what TU is doing, and readily gave me written permission to access the stream. This provides access to another quarter or so up and down stream. Stage measure is taken from top bridge to water surface. Point is crevice between the junction of two concrete rail-forms, 15.6ft from left edge of left form as you face downstream.

Comments: Pool about 200m upstream (N38.169337  W79.468018) in the southern branch/split contained brook trout I'd estimate 8-9'. pH there was 5.0 (same as site) conductivity 39.1 4 higher than main site. It's an interesting note because this stream and its life is a cycle of pooling and flow and I wonder how much different each pool is from another.                      Stream is back to pools; trickle flow in the main bed but the norm seems to be a pooling roughly every 15m - obviously enough to support medium size brook trout. I may revise my estimates of 'low' vs 'norm' levels after I've seen this stream over a year; October may have been closer to normal after the heavy rains. Bank full may be a rare event.                       There were a few deer hunters out. I don't know how I got all those duplicate photos in there....sorry!

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Stream is trickling with a collection of pools every 15m or so. Pools upstream in Jerkemtight hold brook trout of decent size (8-9ft). I did not examine pools on Hamilton closely (bad me...). Leaves did not seem to affect pH however conductivity is up at all monitoring sites over last visit.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Stream is trickling with a collection of pools every 15m or so. Pools upstream in Jerkemtight hold brook trout of decent size (8-9'); I did not examine pools on Hamilton closely (bad me...). Leaves did not seem to affect pH however conductivity is up at all monitoring sites over last visit. On this Hamilton site upstream seems close to dry with pools but downstream is still trickling 'robustly' (as trickle goes). A spring creek confluences downstream of monitoring point 100m; seems to be a fairly consistent flow independent of environmental conditions. Water quality/characteristics may be different here. I'll keep an eye on this creek and maybe take a couple of readings from this confluence in future visits.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Steady hard rain for 2 weeks; unlike upstream monitor sites that are full this downstream site on Hamilton Br has flooded over the bridge in the road and a lot of debris has washed down. Water is still clear but this time registered a little bit of murk in the Secchi tube but I still call it clear; where current isn't whitewater I can easily see bottom. Took several Secchi readings though got anywhere from 120 cm to 110 cm but if I'm honest and don't let the water settle the most often/valid reading seems to be 110. Swift current; water gushing out of the culverts. The stage measuring point is just below of whitewater. My little stream is having a tantrum! I think this level validates what I estimated for bank full. We'll see what happens during Spring rains.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: stage measured as standing in stream: 320 True (9 W decl) to 3rd fence post from road looking NW 21 True (9 W decl) to middle of 3rd culvert from left.                       Dissolved Oxygen (D.O.) measurement taken; method: modified Winkler (titration) using Hanna Instruments Dissolved Oxygen Chemical Test Kit - HI3810. Result: 10.0 ppm (mg/L).                      Pocket tester had difficulty stabilizing. 2 days later after drying out (it was raining hard during data collection) it ceased to function. Readings today make sense given the amount of silt/mud and debris in stream. Compared with HAMIBR001 just an hour prior air temperature is consistent but water temp is considerable colder - about 10 degrees. Don't know that this is significant but water temps of previous excursions have been consistent between this site and HAMIBR001. Defective meter or upstream dynamics? Meter will be replaced anyway.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: stage measured as standing in stream: 320 True (9 W decl) to 3rd fence post from road looking NW 21 True (9 W decl) to middle of 3rd culvert from left.                       Dissolved Oxygen (D.O.) measurement taken; method: modified Winkler (titration) using Hanna Instruments Dissolved Oxygen Chemical Test Kit - HI3810. Result: 8.0 ppm (mg/L).                      Pocket tester had difficulty stabilizing. 2 days later after drying out (it was raining hard during data collection) it ceased to function. Readings today make sense given the amount of silt/mud and debris in stream. Compared with HAMIBR001 just an hour prior air temperature is consistent but water temp is considerable colder - about 10 degrees. Don't know that this is significant but water temps of previous excursions have been consistent between this site and HAMIBR001. Defective meter or upstream dynamics? Meter will be replaced anyway.

Stage measurement changed because the reference log has been washed out. Numerous minnows crayfish in the pool at the monitor pt. Stream flow/trickle is fed by the south branch of Jerkemtight just above the monitor point. Jerkemtight branches into 3 segments above the monitor point then rejoins just above the monitor point. The main streambed is almost completely dry but the branch is feeding a trickle (see pics).

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: This is the observation for July. Although the water was clear and at normal flow there was evidence of recent flow 3' +/- higher due to about 7 in. of rain falling from 7/28-7/31 as recorded by a personal weather station (Weather Underground) located south of Terra Alta. The landowner also reported heavy rain.  The high flow washed out the ford structure constructed by loggers and documented on the 6/28/17 visit. All of the coarse limestone and the pipes were gone with only the large country rock boulders left in the stream. Compare the photos from this this visit with those of 6/28/2017 and 4/26/2017. The landowner thinks they will rebuild a crossing structure.  He also thinks logging will not occur in the Wolf Creek drainage area.

Comments:
Stage measurement changed because 1) a tree on the S bank which reference I used in describing the stage measuring pt toppled across the creek almost on top of the monitor/stage measure pt; 2) reference rocks have been washed out - one actually remains. I used the 6'  downstream and perpendicular to original downed log (still there) to locate stage pt. several measurements taken within  a foot radius of that pt varied the stage by no more than .1 ft so the measure still fairly represents a relative stage to all other measurements I think.  
Dissolved Oxygen (D.O.) measurement method is modified Winkler (titration) using Hanna Instruments Dissolved Oxygen Chemical Test Kit - HI3810. result is 10.0 ppm (mg/L).
pH also measured with Hanna Instruments HI98128 meter reading was 7.39. 
This monitor point looks like it will change character often; it is at a scouring point which of course built a pool that I can be sure will always have water but the high southern bank does seem to take a beating during high water.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments:
stage measured standing in stream: 320 True (9 W decl) to 3rd fence post from road looking NW 21 True (9 W decl) to middle of 3rd culvert from left. Old reference rock has been displaced so best to use the compass coord; prod for the deepest bottom of small cobbles but depth is pretty even.

Dissolved Oxygen (D.O.):  11.0 ppm (mg/L). Measurement method was modified Winkler (titration) using Hanna Instruments Dissolved Oxygen Chemical Test Kit - HI3810.
pH also measured with Hanna Instruments HI98128 meter reading was 7.23. 

Nice flow; light rains during the month; borderline normal flow but I called it low to be consistent with previous observations. Curiously I did not see a single minnow snail or crayfish.

Comments:

This is the coldest it's been at the creek. It had rained about 1.5 inches the day before as recorded in Nellysford. There was a large tree across the creek about 10 meters upstream from my monitoring site. It didn't seem to affect flow. The stream is super clear and so the turbidity measurement is typically 120 cm. The water was still clear but there was some sediment visible this time. I will upload photos later

Comments:
Snow from previous week still evident along banks but this was a balmy bright day. I'm still conflicted about what stage is 'N.'  Current reading is borderline what I'd call N. So far making the call based on my gut plus being consistent with other readings. After a few more months I may adjust based on what seems to be the higher frequency level during the year. However the distinction is somewhat moot because water levels fluctuate widely during the year; precipitation dependent.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments:
There was a beaut of a flood within that past 2 months that overflowed the bank-full banks evidenced by debris and water flow marks in field above banks.
An auto logger (part of the USGS/VADEQ joint effort?) has been installed since my last monitoring on Feb 10 on the opposite side of the bridge where I measure stage. It is an Aquatec Aqualogger 310 TY serial # 2554-032 

Additional measurements not part of prescribed protocol:
Dissolved Oxygen (D.O.):  13.0 ppm (mg/L). Measurement method is modified Winkler (titration) using Hanna Instruments Dissolved Oxygen Chemical Test Kit - HI3810. Averaged 3 titrations.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments:
stage measured standing in stream: 320 True (9 W decl) to 3rd fence post from road looking NW 21 True (9 W decl) to middle of 3rd culvert from left. Old reference rock has been displaced so best to use the compass coord; prod for the deepest bottom of small cobbles but depth is pretty even.

I missed a beut of a flood sometime in the last 2 months that scoured all 3 of my streams in the area. At this site it altered the bed  somewhat. 

Additional measurements not part of prescribed protocol:
Dissolved Oxygen (D.O.):  11.5 ppm (mg/L). Measurement method is modified Winkler (titration) using Hanna Instruments Dissolved Oxygen Chemical Test Kit - HI3810. Averaged 3 titrations.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments:
There has been a severe flood within that past 2 months since my last visit Feb 10. Much debris washed down into the monitoring pt the bottom which was small gravel is significantly altered and is mostly large cobble now; renders stage measuring a bit suspect but it's probably still close enough. More trees are leaning over from the scouring of the banks. There is evidence that the water overflowed the banks which are about 3 feet high above normal water line at the monitor point.

Additional measurements not part of prescribed protocol:
Dissolved Oxygen (D.O.):  12.67 ppm (mg/L). Measurement method is modified Winkler (titration) using Hanna Instruments Dissolved Oxygen Chemical Test Kit - HI3810. Averaged 3 titrations.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Connie Sayles and Kati Holland conducted this stream visit on their own; I (RB) am recording the data they collected and gave to me. In terms of the stage of the stream they described it as 'normal to high' and entered a figure of '5.5 feet' as measured from the base of a tree at the top of the stream's bank to the edge of the stream directly below. This particular stream is difficult to gauge in any way due to steep banks usually too deep to use the stage gauge and lack of safe access areas to do any other kind of measurement. We discussed the situation and need to come up with a consistent way to monitor the stream's stage and chose this particular tree. The tree will be marked with some sturdy and highly visible ribbon and/or tape at the time of the next stream visit.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: 12:10 p.m.  (Howdy Nancy B Catherine Jim and Clyde Clewell).  Narrows of Hans Ck below MVP crossing.  Trees felled prior to 3/31. Not cleared. No E&S measures in place. Some concern and evidence that some erosion and sedimentation may be taking place in heavy rains even now carrying dirt/sawdust along a trail that runs across the ROW out of LOD and then downhill where it fords the stream downstream from our monitoring location.  (To add GPS info and initial photos.) Hope to return to check after rain this weekend.  Temperature difference between ROW and woods outside the LOD measured at 4/10ths on a cloudy day.  Need to continue to measure that differential. The ROW here has disturbed well-established pristine forest that contained high level of biodiversity and indicators of excellent bio conditions now radically changed by the removal of canopy etc.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: This is a site that has been monitored by Robert (Bob) Massengale for over a year. Bob measures the stage from the bridge but I find that difficult. Today I tried to replicate his procedure (as he showed it to me on May 27 2018). The distance to the water from the surface of the bridge was 5'9'; then I subtracted the distance from the surface of the bridge to the bottom of the metal girder (1'6') to get a total of 4'3'. Converted to the decimal system this is 4.25 feet. However I also measured the stage with our measuring stick in midstream out from the middle of the access point (an old road); this measure was .9 feet which is reported below. In the future I hope to continue measuring the stage just with the stick. Assistants: Hersha Evans and Andrew Walker.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Our team received a call from the landowner reporting that the North Fork was running muddy and asking us to come and check measurements. We were glad to receive this alert. The river was indeed muddy--and significantly more turbid at this site (below the MVP work site) than at the two sites upstream (above the MVP work site). The water level was not high. The rain event seems to have involved a heavy downpour but not of long duration which is what occurred at the home of the observer (15 minutes away by car). I could not find a conversion for a turbidity reading of 3; it should be greater than 240 but looking online I found nothing that gave a NTU conversion greater than 240. The photos do not really show the color of the water which was a yellow-y ochre the color (and consistency) of potter's 'slip.' Comparison should be made with my observations on the North Fork on May 19 2018 after several days of rain. Then both the site downstream from MVP (NFROR1004) and the site upstream from MVP (NFROR1002; NFROR1003 was unreachable due to the high water) measured 10 cm in the turbidity tube and there was not a difference in water color.Assistant: Hersha Evans.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: 11:51 AM. Terry Sink landowner saw us at the spring and came to talk with us. He reported receiving a letter from the DEQ reporting that gravel would be (or had been?) placed at the points where MVP had breached the flow of water that leads to his two springs Salmon Spring and Bottom Spring in order to filter out increased sediment. He drew a simplified map (attached as a photo/scan) to explain the dye tracings done decades ago (perhaps sometime between the 1940s and 1960s) that made clear the water sources of both Bottom Spring and Salmon Spring; his drawing also shows how the pipeline trench crosses those paths in three places. The sketched map of course is not to scale. Terry said that this information had been sent to FERC before MVP construction began. Assistant: Hersha Evans.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: We monitored today (rather than on Wednesday Sept 5 as scheduled) in response to an email from landowner David Hancock including two photos (attached below) of the muddy monitoring site on Sunday evening after a rain (about 1.5 inches in his rain gage). There was obvious sediment on the stream bottom and in slower currents outside of the main water channel. In fact the water itself while clear in the narrow main stream channel was off-color in side channels. The water for the turbidity measurement was captured from the main channel the clearest water and it was only 62 cm. The measurement would have been even less had we captured water from a side channel. Pouring water on rocks beyond the present stream flow produced an obvious sediment plume. This turbidity measurement of 62 cm should be compared with the same-day turbidity measurements of 111 and 107 at our North Fork sites above the MVP worksite: NFROR1002 and NFROR1003. Since the trench has been closed and grass is growing where the MVP worksite crosses Catawba Road the additional sediment appears to be coming from the steep uphill portion of the pipeline path across the North Fork. We did observe some minnows lots of 3' fish and a fish that jumped below the bridge. Assistant: Hersha Evans.

We took a turbidity measurement in Dry Run above the backwash: 120 cm. This clear water diluted the sedimentation at this site just below where Dry Run flows into the North Fork in comparison with NFR0R1002 the North Fork just above where Dry Run enters. Assistant: Hersha Evans.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Time: 12:40 pm. We have never before today measured turbidity as less than 120 cm at Salmon Spring. So today's measurement of 46 cm was shocking. Because the water comes out of the pipe in a fairly small stream it looked fairly clear to the eye but capturing the water in a cup or the turbidity tube showed that is was cloudy/off-color. We reported our findings immediately to the family of Linda Parsons Sink and Terry Sink who live across the road because we know that their home and two houses they rent depend on Salmon Spring for their household and drinking water. They were contacting the families in the other two homes. At his request we returned to Salmon Spring and retested the turbidity with Terry Sink; the measurement was 46 cm again at 2:00 pm. We also reported our results to the DEQ Mountain Valley Watch and Wil Orndorff at the DCR. Later Wil went out to test turbidity not only at Salmon Spring (55 cm at 4:50 pm) but also at Dry Run at three places and Mill Creek at two places. This was his conclusion: 'Based on these data I think it's unlikely that Dry Run is the primary source of the turbidity observed in Salmon Spring though Dry Run is upstream and turbidity levels would be expected to fall there first.  I think it's more likely to be some combination of sediment introduced to the system from above (off MVP LOD) and remobilized sediment from the cave system.  I strongly recommend that inspectors (DEQ - MBP FERC MVP) check the LOD from MP ~ 225.5 through 226.7 for failures in erosion control measures releasing sediment to sinkholes or flowing off of the LOD toward sinkholes while also keeping an eye our for subsidence within the LOD.' Assistant: Hersha Evans.

Comments:
Very swift stream flow. We could not sample at midstream because of high water. We measured the stage from 2 feet in (toward the bank) from the midpoint. We spotted no aquatic life. There were no cattle in the field just upstream as there have been recently. Co-monitors: Gavin Washburn and Caitlin Miller. 

The photos of the landowner David Hancock taken October 11 2018 (attached) show just how high the water was two days earlier--flowing OVER his bridge. David reported 5.2 inches of rain in his rain gauge when these photos were taken after a front brought a day of rain followed by the remnants of Hurricane Michael. David reported that he had seen that much water in the North Fork a few times in his life. In addition David supplied photos of his overflow spring which surprisingly had not flowed all summer. It flowed muddy--and heavily--on October 11 the first time he had ever seen it flow muddy.

As we were monitoring we noticed a tree work vehicle headed to the home of the property owner so we suspect there was tree damage there as well. Two other photos show how high and strong the flow was a couple of days ago. One photo shows the bank a little upstream from our monitoring site where the water overflowed its banks and into the adjacent low field. The other photo shows the beat-down grass of that field. Washburn guessed that the low-lying field might long ago have been the bed of Mill Creek before it developed its current twists and turns. Conductivity was lower than normal and turbidity was higher than normal. Co-Monitors: Gavin Washburn and Caitlin.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Large gravel bars have formed on both sides of the stream. One small tree from the right bank at the confluence is down in the stream in addition to the large tree that fell across the stream just above the confluence in the Hurricane Michael aftermath. Some small fish were seen at the confluence. The turbidity measurement in Dry Run was 120 cm. Huge amounts of gravel--processed gravel--have washed into Dry Run and clogged the confluence making pools of water in Dry Run rather than a flowing stream. Co-Monitor: Hersha Evans.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Recent high water has reshaped the stream somewhat carving into the banks in some places and depositing sand along the stream bed in other places. Again we took all measurements except for the stage about 10 feet upstream from the previous monitoring point due to the sycamore tree that was uprooted in the high water and now lies in the stream at our monitoring point. Co-Monitor: Hersha Evans.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Thick sediment is obvious on the bottom rocks. Several minnows (small fish) were seen. The water is receding from our original monitoring point even with the fence post that is becoming more and more slanted and half the distance from the fence post to the edge of the grass. We report below today's measurement at that point: .15 feet. But we also measured at what may become a new monitoring point--about two feet beyond the base of the slanted fence post (see attached photo) and even with the top wire of the fencing (above the hole in the fence): .6 feet. In addition and at David Hancock's suggestion we made alternative arrangements for walking to Bottom Spring after David puts his cows in his hay field and charges up one or more electric fences. At first we had agreed that we would remind him when we were coming and he would turn off the electricity to his fences. But today he showed me where we could park one car off the road at the entrance to one of his gates (to the rocky pasture that is to the left of his house when facing his house) then cross the road and climb over the Sinks' fence and walk left to Bottom Spring. David offered to cut back the underbrush to make access to this little-used gate easier. We confirmed these arrangements later with Terry Sink. David will tell us when he turns on the electric fences for the season and we will use this alternative route through the Sinks' property until he tells us he has turned them off for the season. Co-Monitor: Hersha Evans.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: We saw Terry Sink at one of the rental houses and we were glad he came over to talk with us. We had noticed well-digging equipment at the rental house and indeed the Sinks were putting in two new wells: one for each rental house (having put in a well at their own house some time back for a back-up in case the ram that pumps the spring water was ever broken and had to wait for a part). He said that having realized from the turbidity readings that the source/s of Salmon Spring have been breached (apparently by MVP's construction or sediment from their construction) they could not in good conscience count on the spring to continue to supply safe drinking water to themselves and their two tenants. They felt that had no choice but to dig two new wells for their tenants. He noted that if MVP is completed there will be the added dangers of possible contamination from leaking fracked gas the leaching of the coating of the pipes and any herbicide used to kill woody growth on the right of way. Co-Monitor: Hersha Evans.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Co-Monitors: Hersha Evans and Elizabeth Struthers Malbon. We were not able to complete a full 100' study reach because of the depth of the stream and its temperature. We took our measurements at 5' 15' 25' 35' 45' 55' 65' 70' 75' 85' upstream from the marker sycamore tree on the left (near) bank. At 85' mark on the right bank the water was so deep that one (at least the short ones we are) could not reach down to pick up a pebble without putting one's head under the water which we decided not to do. So all the specimens at the 85' mark were from the left half of the stream. To have moved to a 95' point would have involved wading in waist deep cold water and ducking under a log by lowering oneself more in the water. Instead we went back and did another specimen pick-up at 70 feet. There were places where silt was thick on the stream bottom away from the main water flow.

Also we had several small showers on Sunday and the North Fork was muddy but not as muddy as Friday. Looking at the weather radar and looking up the valley I think that they had several intense showers upstream on Friday and Sunday.' This comment would help explain the high turbidity at all three North Fork sites and Bottom Spring on Monday but the clear water at Mill Creek 009 and Salmon Spring that same day. All sites had high water.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments:
Monitor: Elizabeth Struthers Malbon. Assistant: Andrew Walker. Our conductivity readings were suspiciously and consistently high for all six sites so the results are listed in the comments section for each site but not entered in as data. I had replaced the battery in the conductivity meter because it was not functioning properly at its last use (we substituted the other meter assigned to our team). With the new battery installed the 'bat' light blinks continually; however testing with 1413 fluid prior to this week's monitoring gave a 1420 reading which has been standard for longer than a year for this device. Re-testing after the suspiciously high field measurements gave another 1420 reading. Comparison at all six field sites the following day (7/21/2019; data posted separately) with both meters assigned to our team showed the two to give significantly divergent readings although the other meter which we tested right before taking data tested within normal variation range (1455-1465) for 1413 fluid. The replacement battery for the first conductivity meter was not exactly the kind of battery originally used which could not be found at the store at the time; however it was supposed to be equivalent. I will search for an exact replacement online and we will depend on the second meter until this issue can be resolved. 

Suspicious conductivity reading for this site for 7/20/2019: 1280 micro-Siemens per centimeter. 

Attached are two photos of this site Hancock's bridge during the flash flood of 7/15/2019 taken by David Hancock who had 2+ inches of rain in his rain gauge but heard from two landowners further upstream that they received 3.5 inches in a short period of time. The two lines of debris in the first photo show debris caught on the top edges of the bridge UNDER which we can walk at normal river levels.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Co-Monitors: Elizabeth Struthers Malbon and Lynda Majors. This is a new site upstream from our established most upstream site on the North Fork NFROR1002 and to replace it. This new site is chosen because it is upstream from an ephemeral unnamed tributary that is clearly capable of bringing sediment down from Paris Mountain into the North Fork. We just recently learned about this stream from William Boyd Grubb owner of Paris Mountain Stables from whom we have permission to monitor here (as at NFROR1002 and 1003). Lynda and Elizabeth chose the site on August 4 2019 after exploring the area including hiking up the unnamed tributary for a ways. That ephemeral stream was dry that day but evidence of recent flooding (likely from the July 15 2019 flash flood) was obvious including in the washing away of a barbed wire cattle fence that had been replaced. To reach the monitoring site one walks along the fence of the horse pasture (to the left when facing our previous most upstream site) beyond the horse arena moving to the mown path closer to the stream when it appears. The site is opposite the last two-horse run-in shelter inside the fence. Our path down the bank is becoming obvious beside a willow tree on the right bank and we monitor at midstream about 8 feet downstream from where the trunk of the willow emerges from the bank. We intend to refer to the site as North Fork above the Horse Arena. See four photos.

Comments: A Personal Weather Station in the watershed recorded 0.04 in. rain in the previous 48 hrs. all on the 23rd. The flow was the lowest observed since monitoring inception on 3/28/2017. See photo. Collected a Fall QC sample at this site bottle #QC_0.25_240.  We measured stage from both the downstream and upstream sides of the bridge for a third time. The pool on the upstream side lends itself to more accurate measurement. The measurements on the upstream side to the water have been consistently 1.40 ft. more than the measurements on the downstream side.  After this date we will only measure and report the distance to water on the upstream side with adjustment to maintain consistency with previous readings. Monitoring partner is Corky Kershner.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: This site is about 1/4 mile down stream of pipeline crossing and it was DRY Drought conditions continue resulting in very low water volume from upstream thus diverting the all surface stream to caverns below the stream bed. No readings were taken because there was nothing to measure!  Site STONCR001 approx. 1/2 mile upstream from this site still had surface water flow. Surface water was still flowing at the MVP proposed crossing.  Big Stony (down river) has caverns below the stream bed that accept all water in very low water conditions thus surface water is insufficient to maintain streambed.  No pipeline activity. Thus now a 'sinking creek' at this site only.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Monitor: Hersha Evans. Assistant: Andrew Walker. This turbidity reading of 30 cm (the lowest we have ever recorded for Salmon Spring) was so alarming that the monitor reported it immediately to the owners of the spring and  to Elizabeth Struthers Malbon. (The owners of the spring had already had new wells dug for their tenants who had been using Salmon Spring for household water last fall when we reported a turbidity reading of 42 cm.) It was especially surprising to see a reading of 30 cm for Salmon Spring on the same day as the reading for Bottom Spring was 118 cm. We decided to monitor the turbidity of Salmon Spring on the following days until clearing which took two days.

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Turbidity Monitor: Andrew Walker who reported: 'The water is cloudy and much less clear than normal although an improvement over yesterday. The tube reading is always subjective and because the water conditions were poorer than normal it was difficult to be precise. The water was tested twice and the reading of 75 was from the second sample when the disk could be noticed relatively clearly.'

ProjName: Trout Unlimited WV-VA Water Quality Monitoring Project
Comments: Turbidity Monitor: Andrew Walker who reported: 'The water was demonstrably better today but no idea why. The water was tested twice and the readings identical.' I have an idea why (but of course I cannot prove it): We have indications from dye tracings that one of the sources of Salmon Spring is a sink hole that is in the Right of Way of the Mountain Valley Pipeline; we have previous indications that sediment from the ROW has shown up in the spring water. It is possible that some sediment gets caught in underground passages in karst terrain once the flow of water slows down after a rain event and is washed out by the next rain event even if no new sediment is being washed off the ROW in that second rain event. In three successive days Salmon Spring had turbidity readings of 30 cm 75 cm and 119 cm.
